hands_on_practices.problem:
In the classification of finite groups, a fundamental invariant is the number of conjugacy classes. This number provides strong constraints on the group's structure. Consider a finite group $G$ that is known to possess exactly three distinct conjugacy classes. Which of the following sets contains all possible values for the order of $G$?

A. {2, 3}
B. {3, 4}
C. {3, 6}
D. {4, 6}
E. {6, 8}
